adaptation of some existing buildings, including conversions into residential space; and improvements to public infrastructure and amenities.\n\n! Name\n! Height\n! Year\n\nIn 2011, the United States Navy named the USS \"Jackson\" (LCS-6) in honor of the city.\n\nBULLET::::- Magnolia Roller Vixens, all-female Flat Track Roller Derby League. Formed in 2008, dissolved in 2016.\n\nBULLET::::- Mississippi Veterans Memorial Stadium, concerts, football (home of Jackson State University)\nBULLET::::- Mississippi Coliseum, basketball, hockey, track, rodeo, concerts\nBULLET::::- Smith Wills Stadium – baseball, softball, football, soccer, concerts (home of the Belhaven College baseball team)\n\nBULLET::::- Baseball\nBULLET::::- Mississippi Braves – Southern League AA affiliate of the Atlanta Braves; Trustmark Park in Pearl, Mississippi\nBULLET::::- Soccer\nBULLET::::- Mississippi Brilla – soccer club which plays in the Premier Developmental League\nBULLET::::- Rugby Union\nBULLET::::- Jackson Rugby Football Club – men's 15s amateur rugby team\nBULLET::::- Football\nBULLET::::- Mississippi Maddogs – plays in the Magnolia Football League\n\nBULLET::::- Baseball\nBULLET::::- Jackson Mets – former Texas League AA affiliate of the New York Mets (1975–1990); Smith-Wills Stadium\nBULLET::::- Jackson Generals – former Texas League AA affiliate of the Houston Astros (1991–1999); Smith-Wills Stadium\nBULLET::::- Jackson Diamond Kats – of the independent Texas-Louisiana League (later changed its name to the Central Baseball League) (2000); Smith-Wills Stadium\nBULLET::::- Jackson Senators – independent (2001–2004); Smith-Wills Stadium\nBULLET::::- Basketball\nBULLET::::- Jackson Wildcats – United States Basketball League\nBULLET::::- Jackson Rage – World Basketball Association (2004)\nBULLET::::- Mississippi Hardhats – World Basketball Association (2005)\nBULLET::::- Jackson Showboats – American Basketball Association\nBULLET::::- Hockey\nBULLET::::- Jackson Bandits – East Coast Hockey 