{"id": "16192", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=16192", "title": "January 14", "text": "January 14\n\nIn the 20th and 21st centuries the Julian calendar is 13 days behind the Gregorian calendar, thus January 14 is sometimes celebrated as New Year's Day (Old New Year) by religious groups who use the Julian calendar.\n\nBULLET::::- 1236 – King Henry III of England marries Eleanor of Provence.\nBULLET::::- 1301 – Andrew III of Hungary dies, ending the Árpád dynasty in Hungary.\nBULLET::::- 1343 – Arnošt of Pardubice becomes the last bishop of Prague and, subsequently, the first Archbishop of Prague.\nBULLET::::- 1539 – Spain annexes Cuba.\nBULLET::::- 1639 – The \"Fundamental Orders\", the first written constitution that created a government, is adopted in Connecticut.\nBULLET::::- 1761 – The Third Battle of Panipat is fought in India between the Afghans under Ahmad Shah Durrani and the Marathas.\nBULLET::::- 1784 – American Revolutionary War: Ratification Day, United States - Congress ratifies the Treaty of Paris with Great Britain.\nBULLET::::- 1814 – Treaty of Kiel: Frederick VI of Denmark cedes the Kingdom of Norway to Charles XIII of Sweden in return for Pomerania.\nBULLET::::- 1822 – Greek War of Independence: Acrocorinth is captured by Theodoros Kolokotronis and Demetrios Ypsilantis.\nBULLET::::- 1858 – Napoleon III of France escapes an assassination attempt made by Felice Orsini and his accomplices in Paris.\nBULLET::::- 1907 – An earthquake in Kingston, Jamaica kills more than 1,000 people.\nBULLET::::- 1911 – Roald Amundsen's South Pole expedition makes landfall on the eastern edge of the Ross Ice Shelf.\nBULLET::::- 1939 – Norway claims Queen Maud Land in Antarctica.\nBULLET::::- 1943 – World War II: Japan begins Operation Ke, the successful operation to evacuate its forces from Guadalcanal during the Guadalcanal Campaign.\nBULLET::::- 1943 – World War II: Franklin D. Roosevelt becomes the first President of the United States to travel by airplane while in office when he flies from Miami to Morocco to meet with Winston Churchill.\nBULLET::::- 1943 – World War II: Franklin D. Roosevelt and Winston Churchill begin the Casablanca Conference to discuss strategy and study the next phase of the war.\nBULLET::::- 1950 – The first prototype of the MiG-17 makes its maiden flight.\nBULLET::::- 1952 – NBC's long-running morning news program \"Today\" debuts, with host Dave Garroway.\nBULLET::::- 1953 – Josip Broz Tito is inaugurated as the first President of Yugoslavia.\nBULLET::::- 1954 – The Hudson Motor Car Company merges with Nash-Kelvinator Corporation forming the American Motors Corporation.\nBULLET::::- 1957 – Kripalu Maharaj was named fifth Jagadguru (world teacher) after giving seven days of speeches before 500 Hindu scholars.\nBULLET::::- 1960 – The Reserve Bank of Australia, the country's central bank and banknote issuing authority, is established.\nBULLET::::- 1967 – Counterculture of the 1960s: The Human Be-In takes place in San Francisco, California's Golden Gate Park, launching the Summer of Love.\nBULLET::::- 1967 - \"The New York Times\" reports that the U.S. Army is conducting secret germ warfare experiments.\nBULLET::::- 1969 – USS Enterprise fire: An accidental explosion aboard the near Hawaii kills 28 people.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – Queen Margrethe II of Denmark ascends the throne, the first Queen of Denmark since 1412 and the first Danish monarch not named Frederick or Christian since 1513.\nBULLET::::- 1973 – Elvis Presley's concert \"Aloha from Hawaii\" is broadcast live via satellite, and sets the record as the most watched broadcast by an individual entertainer in television history.\nBULLET::::- 1993 – In Poland's worst peacetime maritime disaster, ferry MS \"Jan Heweliusz\" sinks off the coast of Rügen, drowning 55 passengers and crew; nine crew-members are saved.\nBULLET::::- 2000 – A United Nations tribunal sentences five Roman Catholic Bosnian Croats to up to 25 years in prison for the 1993 killing of more than 100 Bosnian Muslims.\nBULLET::::- 2004 – The national flag of the Republic of Georgia, the so-called \"five cross flag\", is restored to official use after a hiatus of some 500 years.\nBULLET::::- 2010 – Yemen declares an open war against the terrorist group al-Qaeda.\nBULLET::::- 2011 – Former president of Tunisia, Zine El Abidine Ben Ali flees his country to Saudi Arabia after a series of street demonstrations against his regime and corrupt policies, asking for freedom, rights and democracy, considered as the anniversary of the Tunisian Revolution and the birth of the Arab Spring.\n\nBULLET::::- 83 BC – Mark Antony, Roman general and politician (d. 30 BCE)\nBULLET::::- 1131 – Valdemar I of Denmark (d. 1182)\nBULLET::::- 1273 – Joan I of Navarre, queen regnant of Navarre, queen consort of France (d. 1305)\nBULLET::::- 1451 – Franchinus Gaffurius, Italian composer and theorist (d. 1522)\nBULLET::::- 1477 – Hermann of Wied, German archbishop (d. 1552)\nBULLET::::- 1476 – Anne St Leger, Baroness de Ros, English baroness (d. 1526)\nBULLET::::- 1507 – Catherine of Austria, Queen of Portugal (d. 1578)\nBULLET::::- 1507 – Luca Longhi, Italian painter (d. 1580)\nBULLET::::- 1551 – Abu'l-Fazl ibn Mubarak, Grand vizier of emperor Akbar (d. 1602)\nBULLET::::- 1552 – Alberico Gentili, Italian-English academic and jurist (d. 1608)\nBULLET::::- 1615 – John Biddle, English minister and theologian (d. 1662)\nBULLET::::- 1683 – Gottfried Silbermann, German instrument maker (d. 1753)\nBULLET::::- 1684 – Johann Matthias Hase, German mathematician, astronomer, and cartographer (d. 1742)\nBULLET::::- 1684 – Jean-Baptiste van Loo, French painter (d. 1745)\nBULLET::::- 1699 – Jakob Adlung, German organist, historian, and theorist (d. 1762)\nBULLET::::- 1700 – Picander, German poet and playwright (d. 1764)\nBULLET::::- 1702 – Emperor Nakamikado of Japan (d. 1737)\nBULLET::::- 1705 – Jean-Baptiste Charles Bouvet de Lozier, French sailor, explorer, and politician (d. 17